{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01WfLaYNDkqev4UkTUwvfXzv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EQNzUmnHVaFtgtQrTEAgYD","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-2-2-observability-hook-enforcement && STORY_CONTENT=$(cat story.md) && cat > /tmp/verify-prompt-2-2.txt << 'PROMPT_DELIM'\nYou are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file `story.md` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Read it now.\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n\nThe container has the following tools installed:\n- `codeharness` — the project CLI\n- `curl`, `jq` — for querying observability endpoints\n- `node`, `npm` — Node.js runtime\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n\n- **VictoriaLogs** (logs): `http://localhost:9428`\n- **VictoriaMetrics** (metrics): `http://localhost:8428`\n- **VictoriaTraces** (traces): `http://localhost:16686`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command you run, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n```\n\n- If the response contains one or more log entries, the code path has observability coverage. Note the count in your proof.\n- If the response contains zero log entries, the code path is a silent gap. Include this tag:\n  `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction`\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `verification/2-2-observability-hook-enforcement-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```text\n## AC N: <description>\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages.** Never use bare ``` fences without a language tag.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`** — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** — there is no `src/` directory in this workspace.\n3. **Report REAL failures** — if a feature does not work, report that as a verification failure. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** — reading docs alone is not evidence. You must execute commands and capture output.\n5. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things that are genuinely impossible to automate** — NOT for infrastructure problems.\n6. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.**\n\n### Story-specific verification guidance\n\nFor this story (observability hook enforcement), here is how to verify each AC:\n\n**AC 1** (hook blocks when static coverage < target):\n- Create a test project directory in the container\n- Set up a sprint-state.json with static coverage at 72% and target at 80%\n- Include some gap entries in the observability.static.gaps array\n- Run `codeharness observability-gate --json` and verify exit code is 1, output shows current 72 vs target 80\n\n**AC 2** (hook allows when both pass):\n- Set up sprint-state.json with static coverage at 85% (>= 80% target) and runtime at 65% (>= 60% target)\n- Run `codeharness observability-gate --json` and verify exit code is 0\n\n**AC 3** (block message includes gap details):\n- With the failing state from AC 1 (include gaps in sprint-state.json under observability.static.gaps)\n- Run `codeharness observability-gate` (without --json) and verify the text output includes file/line gap details\n- Run with --json and verify the gaps array in JSON output is non-empty with file/line/description fields\n\nFor the hook test, run the hook script directly:\n```\ndocker exec codeharness-verify sh -c 'HARNESS_CLI=codeharness bash /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/hooks/pre-commit-gate.sh; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'\n```\nPROMPT_DELIM\necho \"Prompt written, $(wc -c < /tmp/verify-prompt-2-2.txt) bytes\"","description":"Write verification prompt to file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4615,"cache_read_input_tokens":56326,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4615},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2fa32674-558d-4231-8eb7-1997dc535a41","uuid":"f7c595b3-24bb-41c4-9727-5f8f345fab9d"}
